dot("$(3,1)$", (3,1), SE);
[/asy]

Since the square has vertices on the parabola $y = x^2,$ the points $(a,a^2)$ and $(b,b^2)$ must lie on the square.  Then
\[\sqrt{5(b - a)^2} = \sqrt{(b - a)^2 + (b^2 - a^2)^2}.\]This simplifies to $4(b - a)^2 = (b^2 - a^2)^2,$ or $(b - a)^2 (4 - (b + a)^2) = 0.$  Since $b \neq a,$ $b + a = 2.$

Then the side length of the square is $\sqrt{5(b - a)^2} = \sqrt{5(b - 2 + b)^2} = \sqrt{20(b - 1)^2} = 2 \sqrt{5} |b - 1|,$ so the area of the square is $20(b - 1)^2.$

We want to minimize $20(b - 1)^2.$  Since $b + a = 2,$ $a = 2 - b.$  The points $(a,2a - 17)$ and $(b,2b - 17)$ lie on the parabola $y = x^2,$ so
\begin{align*}
2a - 17 &= a^2, \\
2b - 17 &= b^2.
\end{align*}These equations factor as $(a - 2)(a + 8) = 0$ and $(b - 2)(b + 8) = 0.$  Since $a$ and $b$ are the $x$-coordinates of points on the parabola $y = x^2,$ $a$ and $b$ must be between $-8$ and 2.  Hence, $a = 2$ and $b = 2.$  The area of the square is then $20(b - 1)^2 = \boxed{20}.$

